1
00:00:00,140 --> 00:00:04,250
In this video we are going to learn event sourcing pattern.

2
00:00:04,340 --> 00:00:06,530
What is the event sourcing pattern?

3
00:00:06,980 --> 00:00:13,250
As you know that most of the applications saves data into databases with the current state of the entity.

4
00:00:13,790 --> 00:00:20,990
For example, if the user change email address into our application, the user email field updated with

5
00:00:20,990 --> 00:00:22,640
the latest updated one.

6
00:00:22,970 --> 00:00:28,490
So email information overwrite the existing field of email in the user table.

7
00:00:28,970 --> 00:00:33,110
By this way, we always know the latest status of the data.

8
00:00:33,590 --> 00:00:39,110
This is the traditional model that works fine to overwrite existing field when something changed.

9
00:00:40,410 --> 00:00:47,010
But in large scale architectures frequently update database operations can negatively impact the database

10
00:00:47,010 --> 00:00:50,460
performance, responsiveness, and limits of scalability.

11
00:00:51,600 --> 00:00:58,020
In order to solve this problem, event sourcing pattern offers to persist each action that affects the

12
00:00:58,020 --> 00:01:03,330
data into the event store database and call all these actions as an event.

13
00:01:04,019 --> 00:01:09,300
So we can say that instead of saving the latest status of data into databases.

14
00:01:09,360 --> 00:01:16,230
Event Sourcing pattern offers to save all events into database with sequential order of data events.

15
00:01:16,260 --> 00:01:19,350
These events database called event store.

16
00:01:21,240 --> 00:01:28,170
That means instead of overriding the data into table, it creates a new record for each change to data

17
00:01:28,170 --> 00:01:30,000
and it becomes sequential.

18
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:31,650
List of the past events.

19
00:01:32,310 --> 00:01:39,120
By this way, events store database become the source of truth for the data and these sequential list

20
00:01:39,120 --> 00:01:45,540
using for generating materialized views that represent the final state of the data in order to perform

21
00:01:45,540 --> 00:01:46,260
queries.

22
00:01:47,250 --> 00:01:53,820
So that means these events store convert to read database with following the materialized view pattern.

23
00:01:54,510 --> 00:02:00,900
This convert operation can handle by publish subscribe pattern with publish events with using the message

24
00:02:00,900 --> 00:02:01,980
broker systems.

25
00:02:02,370 --> 00:02:09,840
Also, these event list gives ability to reply events at given certain timestamp, and by this way it

26
00:02:09,840 --> 00:02:13,560
is able to breathe latest status of data with replying to events.

